        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>How to: Flatten a Curved Path into a Line</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Drawing2D.GraphicsPath&gt;</ph> object stores a sequence of lines and Bézier splines.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can add several types of curves (ellipses, arcs, cardinal splines) to a path, but each curve is converted to a Bézier spline before it is stored in the path.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Flattening a path consists of converting each Bézier spline in the path to a sequence of straight lines.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following illustration shows a path before and after flattening.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">![</bpt>Straight Lines and Curves<ept id="p1">]</ept><bpt id="p2">(../../../../docs/framework/winforms/advanced/media/aboutgdip02-art32a.gif "</bpt>AboutGdip02_Art32A<ept id="p2">")</ept></source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>To Flatten a Path</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>call the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Drawing2D.GraphicsPath.Flatten%2A&gt;</ph> method of a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Drawing2D.GraphicsPath&gt;</ph> object.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Drawing2D.GraphicsPath.Flatten%2A&gt;</ph> method receives a flatness argument that specifies the maximum distance between the flattened path and the original path.</source>
        </trans-unit>
